# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

## Key Problems in the Original Code

| Issue | Why it breaks on .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — removed in .NET 5+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Still exists but unreliable; throws `ThreadInterruptedException` only from managed blocking calls |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` + `Queue` | Works, but is a hand-rolled producer/consumer — replaced by `Channel<T>` |
| Race condition | Multiple `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` lose items (only one dequeue per signal) |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _runTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        // ReadAllAsync yields items as they arrive; blocks asynchronously
        // when empty; completes when the writer is closed.
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        // Signal no more items — RunLoopAsync will drain and exit.
        _channel.Writer.Complete();

        if (_cts is not null && _runTask is not null)
        {
            // If it doesn't drain in time, cancel the token.
            using var timeoutCts = new CancellationTokenSource(
                timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

            try
            {
                await _runTask.WaitAsync(timeoutCts.Token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Timeout elapsed — force-cancel the loop.
                await _cts.CancelAsync();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## Migration Cheat-Sheet

| .NET Framework pattern | .NET 8 replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread` + `Start()` | `Task.Run()` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `CancellationToken` |
| `ManualResetEvent` | `Channel<T>` or `SemaphoreSlim.WaitAsync` |
| `lock` + `Queue<T>` | `Channel<T>` (thread-safe, backpressure-aware) |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `await task.WaitAsync(timeout)` |

## Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`Thread.Abort` is gone** — no forced termination exists. All cancellation must be *cooperative* via `CancellationToken`. Long-running `Handle()` calls should accept and check a token too.

2. **Race condition fix** — the original loses items when multiple `Enqueue` calls fire before `Reset`. `Channel<T>` eliminates this entirely.

3. **Don't use `BlockingCollection<T>`** — it works but blocks a thread. `Channel<T>` is async-native and avoids thread-pool starvation.

4. **Bounded vs. unbounded** — use `CreateBounded<T>(capacity)` if producers can outpace consumers; it applies backpressure automatically.

5. **Exception handling** — if `Handle()` throws, the loop dies silently. Add a `try/catch` inside the loop or attach a continuation to `_runTask` to surface errors.
